# Cloud Computing Lab - Program 7
## Program 7: Building Own Static Website and Hosting Application



# Part A: Hosting Static Website on EC2

---

## Step 1: Launch Ubuntu EC2 Instance

Go to:
AWS Console → EC2 Dashboard → Instances

Click:

Launch instances

Enter instance name:

PG07-Static-EC2

Choose AMI:

Ubuntu Server

Choose instance type:

t2.micro

or:

t3.micro

Choose key pair:

cloud-lab-key

In Network settings, click:

Edit

Select:

VPC: Lab-VPC
Subnet: Public-Subnet
Auto-assign public IP: Enable

Use existing security group:

Lab-SG

Make sure the security group has these inbound rules:

Type: SSH
Port: 22
Source: My IP or 0.0.0.0/0
Type: HTTP
Port: 80
Source: 0.0.0.0/0

Optional:

Type: HTTPS
Port: 443
Source: 0.0.0.0/0

Click:

Launch instance

Wait until the instance state becomes:

Running

Copy the public IPv4 address of the EC2 instance.

Step 2: Connect to EC2 from Ubuntu Terminal

Open local Ubuntu terminal.

Go to the folder where the key pair is downloaded:

cd ~/Downloads

Give permission to the key file:

chmod 400 cloud-lab-key.pem

Connect to EC2:

ssh -i cloud-lab-key.pem ubuntu@EC2-PUBLIC-IP

Example:

ssh -i cloud-lab-key.pem ubuntu@13.233.xx.xx

After successful login, terminal will show:

ubuntu@ip-10-1-1-xx:~$

This means we are inside the Ubuntu EC2 instance.

Step 3: Install Apache Web Server

Inside the EC2 terminal, run:

sudo apt update -y
sudo apt install -y apache2
sudo systemctl start apache2
sudo systemctl enable apache2
sudo systemctl status apache2

Expected status:

active (running)
Step 4: Create Static Website on EC2

Go to Apache web root directory:

cd /var/www/html

Remove default Apache page:

sudo rm -f index.html

Create new index.html file:

sudo nano index.html

Paste the following code:

<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
    <title>PG-07 Static Website</title>
    <style>
        body {
            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
            background: #f4f6f8;
            margin: 0;
            padding: 0;
        }

        header {
            background: #232f3e;
            color: white;
            padding: 30px;
            text-align: center;
        }

        section {
            margin: 40px auto;
            width: 80%;
            background: white;
            padding: 30px;
            border-radius: 10px;
        }

        h1 {
            margin: 0;
        }

        .box {
            padding: 15px;
            background: #e8f0fe;
            margin-top: 20px;
            border-left: 5px solid #1a73e8;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>

<header>
    <h1>PG-07: Static Website Hosting</h1>
    <p>Hosted on AWS EC2 Ubuntu Instance</p>
</header>

<section>
    <h2>Cloud Computing Lab</h2>
    <p>This is a static website hosted using Apache web server on an Ubuntu EC2 instance.</p>

    <div class="box">
        <h3>Website Details</h3>
        <p><strong>Service Used:</strong> Amazon EC2</p>
        <p><strong>Web Server:</strong> Apache2</p>
        <p><strong>Operating System:</strong> Ubuntu</p>
    </div>
</section>

</body>
</html>

Save the file:

Ctrl + O
Enter
Ctrl + X

Restart Apache:

sudo systemctl restart apache2
Step 5: Open EC2 Website in Browser

Copy the EC2 public IPv4 address.

Open in browser:

http://EC2-PUBLIC-IP

Example:

http://13.233.xx.xx

Expected output:

PG-07: Static Website Hosting
Hosted on AWS EC2 Ubuntu Instance

This completes static website hosting using EC2.

Part B: Hosting Static Website on Amazon S3
Step 6: Create Static Website File on Local Ubuntu

Open local Ubuntu terminal.

Create a folder:

mkdir -p ~/pg07-static-site
cd ~/pg07-static-site

Create index.html:

nano index.html

Paste the following code:

<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
    <title>PG-07 S3 Static Website</title>
    <style>
        body {
            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
            background: #eef2f7;
            text-align: center;
            padding: 50px;
        }

        .card {
            background: white;
            padding: 30px;
            border-radius: 10px;
            width: 70%;
            margin: auto;
            box-shadow: 0 0 10px #aaa;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <div class="card">
        <h1>PG-07: Static Website Hosted on Amazon S3</h1>
        <p>This website is uploaded from Ubuntu desktop and hosted using S3 Static Website Hosting.</p>
        <h3>Cloud Computing Lab</h3>
    </div>
</body>
</html>

Save the file:

Ctrl + O
Enter
Ctrl + X
Step 7: Create S3 Bucket

Go to:

AWS Console → S3 → Create bucket

Enter a globally unique bucket name:

musaib-pg07-static-website-20260701

Region:

Asia Pacific Mumbai / ap-south-1

In Block Public Access settings for this bucket, untick:

Block all public access

Tick the acknowledgement checkbox.

Click:

Create bucket
Step 8: Upload Website File to S3

Open the created bucket.

Go to:

Objects → Upload

Click:

Add files

Select:

index.html

Click:

Upload

After upload, confirm that index.html is present in the root of the bucket.

Correct:

index.html

Wrong:

folder/index.html
Step 9: Enable Static Website Hosting

Open the S3 bucket.

Go to:

Properties

Scroll down to:

Static website hosting

Click:

Edit

Select:

Enable

Hosting type:

Host a static website

Index document:

index.html

Error document:

index.html

Click:

Save changes

After saving, copy the Bucket website endpoint shown in the Static Website Hosting section.

It looks like:

http://bucket-name.s3-website.ap-south-1.amazonaws.com

or:

http://bucket-name.s3-website-ap-south-1.amazonaws.com

Important: Always copy the exact endpoint from the S3 bucket properties instead of typing it manually.

Step 10: Add Bucket Policy

Go to:

S3 → Your bucket → Permissions

Scroll to:

Bucket policy

Click:

Edit

Paste the following policy.

Replace YOUR-BUCKET-NAME with your actual bucket name.

{
  "Version": "2012-10-17",
  "Statement": [
    {
      "Sid": "PublicReadForStaticWebsite",
      "Effect": "Allow",
      "Principal": "*",
      "Action": "s3:GetObject",
      "Resource": "arn:aws:s3:::YOUR-BUCKET-NAME/*"
    }
  ]
}

Example:

{
  "Version": "2012-10-17",
  "Statement": [
    {
      "Sid": "PublicReadForStaticWebsite",
      "Effect": "Allow",
      "Principal": "*",
      "Action": "s3:GetObject",
      "Resource": "arn:aws:s3:::musaib-pg07-static-website-20260701/*"
    }
  ]
}

Click:

Save changes

Correct resource format:

arn:aws:s3:::bucket-name/*

Wrong resource format:

arn:aws:s3:::bucket-name*
Step 11: Open S3 Website Endpoint

Go to:

S3 → Your bucket → Properties → Static website hosting

Copy the exact Bucket website endpoint.

Open it in browser:

http://bucket-website-endpoint

Example:

http://musaib-pg07-static-website-20260701.s3-website.ap-south-1.amazonaws.com

Expected output:

PG-07: Static Website Hosted on Amazon S3
This website is uploaded from Ubuntu desktop and hosted using S3 Static Website Hosting.
